Predicting Sale Prices of Homes in Ames, Iowa¶

Kirstin Pruitt, Mahsa Sheikhihafshejani, Larry Yu

Business Understanding¶

Overview of Dataset¶

The dataset chosen for Lab One is the Ames housing dataset gathered and contributed by Dean De Cock of Truman State University and made widely available by Kaggle [1]. The purpose of the dataset is to predict the final sale price of individual homes in Ames, Iowa, based on various characteristics described by the 79 explanatory variables. This detailed collection of home features was gathered to highlight that there is much more to the real estate scene than what meets the eye. It proves that the price of a house is the product of a culmination of factors such as railroad proximity and slope of a property, rather than simply asking the run-of-the-mill questions like how many bedrooms does it have or is there a white picket fence? The dataset contains training and testing data, which consist of 1460 and 1459 observations, respectively. Of the aforementioned 79 explanatory variables, 46 are categorical (23 nominal and 23 ordinal) and 33 are numeric (14 discrete and 19 continuous).

The 46 categorical variables involved in the datasets contain a considerable range of classes under which the houses in the study fall. The nominal variables, which have no respective underlying ranking system, include information about the house that describe such things as dwelling, location, style, materials, heating and electrical systems, and garages. On the other hand, the ordinal variables rate numerous features and characteristics of the property involved in the sale.

The 14 discrete variables were incorporated to evaluate specific numbers of features in the home such as number of bedrooms, bathrooms (full and half), and kitchens on the basement level and above ground. Number of cars that could fit in the garage and year it was built, number of fireplaces, and information about dates of construction, remodeling, and sales were also encompassed by these discrete variables.

The 19 continuous variables consist mostly of square footage of different spaces within the home. In some instances, those spaces are broken down into separate variables based on the finish of the space, occurring, for instance, with basements and porches, which have four and five respective categories. Still other variables that are commonly expected in the real estate scene are included such as lot size in square feet and above ground square footage of living area. The remaining variables in this category that do not contain information about area dimensions are monetary values of miscellaneous features and, of course, Sale Price (in the training set, but not in the test set).

The Prediction Task¶

Predicting the sale price of homes is an important task in todays market. Home buyers want assurance that theyre getting the best deal and not overpaying for a home, while sellers are looking to maximize their profits - a vicious cycle that has become quite monstrous when coupled with inflation rates. The typical home buyer will look at a few features like the basement, the master bathroom, and how many cars fit in the garage. They may not realize that the home is actually within 200 feet of a railroad if the home is strategically shown at times when trains arent running. This dataset challenges virtually every feature one could think of for homes in Ames, Iowa to most accurately determine a good sale price and ultimately what the final sale price will be of a home - which may not be the same.

It is important to note that according to the US Census Bureau, the estimated median home value of owner-occupied units (2016-2020) was \$ 213, 500, but the median household income (in 2020 dollars) between 2016 and 2020 was \\$ 50, 783 [2]. From this, it is evident that home buying is a significant undertaking for the majority of occupants of the town. Thus is the essence of the incentive behind our prediction task - protecting people from getting ripped off when spending their hard-earned money.

In order for our prediction model to be rendered useful to the home-buying market of Ames, Iowa, we seek to accurately predict sale prices within a margin of error of 4.21%, which is reflective of the average inflation rate of the housing market between 1967 and 2022 [3]. The thought behind this is home buyers are frequently aware of inflation and are expected to account for this in some way when trying to come up with the money to purchase a home. Utilizing this relatively low percentage as a threshold, the model will need to more accurately predict the sale prices of more affordable housing in the Ames market, while having a bit more of a buffer when it comes to more expensive homes. When considering this approach, it is geared toward the protection of the average home buyer, who, in line with Census Bureau statistics, does not likely have the extra income to afford a drastic undershoot on our end. On the flip side of that, there are not many houses in Ames that go for $ 300, 000 and above. Given that the supply of these homes is fairly low, we expect the demand for them in more affluent parts to drive up the sale prices, so our margin of error accounts for more flexibility on the predicted sale prices of homes whose buyers are more likely to have spare change, if you will. Plot 0 below shows the distribution of sale prices in our dataset.

Presence of 'NA' as categorical level¶
Some of the features in this dataset contain 'NA' categories that do not indicate missing values, and we should replace them. Features containing 'NA' categories are 'Alley', 'BsmtQual', 'BsmtCond', 'BsmtExposure', 'BsmtFinType1','BsmtFinType2', 'FireplaceQu', 'GarageType', 'GarageFinish', 'GarageQual','GarageCond', 'PoolQC', 'Fence', and 'MiscFeature'. First, we change 'NA' to 'none' to be able to distinguish them.











In [75]:



     


# replace NAs that are meaningful to the dataset. 
# according to data dictionary, the following variables have 'NA' categories that are *not* indicative of 
# missing values
data[['Alley', 'BsmtQual', 'BsmtCond', 'BsmtExposure', 'BsmtFinType1', 
      'BsmtFinType2', 'FireplaceQu', 'GarageType', 'GarageFinish', 'GarageQual', 
      'GarageCond', 'PoolQC', 'Fence', 'MiscFeature']] = data[['Alley', 'BsmtQual', 
                                                               'BsmtCond', 'BsmtExposure', 'BsmtFinType1', 
                                                               'BsmtFinType2', 'FireplaceQu', 'GarageType',
                                                               'GarageFinish', 'GarageQual', 'GarageCond', 
                                                               'PoolQC', 'Fence', 'MiscFeature']].fillna('none')



     















Ordinal categories¶
Some of our features have the ordinal type of categorical variable. We have sorted these categories and applied numbers to convert them into sensible numeric terms. For example, 'GarageCond' has six categories which are sorted as 'none','Po','Fa','TA','Gd','Ex' and show the increasing condition rating of the garage. We assign numbers 0 to 5 to these ordinal categories.

Presense of conflicting information¶
In the data related to the following three spaces in the house, there is some conflicting information which needs to be resolved:


    

  • Pool
    • 

  • Gararge
    • 

  • Basement
    • 



Pool


The pool quality PoolQC is the feature that contributes to a home's price and contains the (0)'NA' category, which means having no pool. Other types are (5) 'Ex', (4) 'Gd', (3) 'TA', and (2) 'Fa,' which correspond to excellent, good, average, and fair quality.
Another feature related to the house pool is the 'PoolArea', which is the area of the pool reported in square feet. Looking at these two columns, we noticed some instances have a pool area, but a 0 for their pool quality, which means having no pool. Since this is illogical, we change their pool quality by looking at the house's overall quality reported in the 'OverallQual' columns and assign meaningful pool quality to these instances.

Garage


A house's value is impacted by the size and quality of the garage. Our dataset has a group of features associated with the garage space. These features are GarageType,GarageFinish, GarageFinish, GarageCars, GarageArea, GarageQual, and GarageCond.


GarageType, GarageFinish, GarageQual, and GarageCond are categorical features indicating the garage's location, finish state of the garage, and the quality and condition of the garage, respectively. These four features have the 'NA' category, which indicates that there is no garage and were previously recoded as 0.


Two features, GarageCars and GarageArea, indicate the garage's size in car capacity and square feet. Zero values for these two features mean the house has no garage space.


There are some instances in our data with features showing there is a garage and others not in agreement. We find these instances and remove these conflicting pieces of information.

Basement


BsmtQual, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinType2,  BsmtFinSF2, BsmtUnfSF, and TotalBsmtSF are features related to the house's basement.


BsmtQual, BsmtCond, and BsmtExposure represent the height of the basement, the general condition of the basement, and walkout or garden level walls of the basement, respectively.


BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinType2,  BsmtFinSF2 are ratings of the basement finished area, and finished square feet of first type and second type of the basement (if there exists multiple types).


BsmtUnfSF and TotalBsmtSF are finished square feet of the basement area and total square feet of basement area, respectively.


BsmtFullBath and BsmtHalfBath represent the number of basement full bathrooms, and half bathrooms.


Similar to the garage-related features, there is some conflicting information about the basement. Some features report no basement, and others have information for an existing basement. We solve this issue by replacing these values or removing them to be imputed later. Also, some missing data can be filled using other related information.

Summary of Data Understanding¶
The data types are mostly addressed in detail in the Overview of Dataset section above, but when the dataset was loaded in, it consisted of 43 objects representing categorical variables, 33 int64, and 3 float64 types representing numeric predictors. This is slightly off from the description because some ordinal variables were actually observed as numbers while others need to be recoded to enforce their order. This count does not include Id (int64), Sale Price (int64), or the added data variable (object) to separate the training and test sets following data cleaning. The training and test sets were intuitively combined in a way that ensured data leakage would not be an issue since only qualities of an instance were used for the manual imputation techniques. This approach is inspired by and adapted from the Bruin kernel [4].


While the dataset consists of 79 predictors, the most prominent attributes are qualitative, ordinal type features that describe the condition and quality of various aspects of the home - like the kitchen, exterior, garage, and basement - as well as some continuous variables that describe things like the number of full baths, half baths, and bedrooms, and how many cars fit in the garage or lot square footage. There were also attributes like zoning classification and neighborhood that were categorical, nominal variables that would ultimately have to be converted to some sort of dummy variables for prediction modeling and correlation analysis.


There were 14 nominal variables whose classes included an NA category which corresponded to none - for example, pool and fireplace quality, among others. These categories had to be replaced with a meaningful name so as to not be mistaken for missing values. The next step in the data cleaning process was to recode the ordinal variables to reflect their ranks - this included variables like lot shape, garage condition, and heating quality (to name a few). Next, some disguised missingness was addressed by looking at observations whose continuous variables for area / square footage indicated the presence of features whose qualities were unranked - most of these instances were manually imputed based on the overall quality of the home and other relevant features that were unique to each property. Some of the variables whose classes originally demonstrated an NA category had camouflaged missing values, so these were found throughout the dataset and reset as NAs for future automated k-nearest neighbors imputation. These techniques utilized table analyses to compare a multitude of features at once rather than visualizing the distributions of individual attributes - both a pro and con of a high-dimension dataset.


Once the manual imputation was complete, the data was left with 702 NAs that needed to be filled. There were 12 numeric and 6 categorical predictors that were affected by this data missingness. Since the k-nearest neighbors imputation technique does exactly what it sounds like it does - uses the k, a number set by the user, nearest neighbors to automatically fill in missing values of numeric predictors - the data variable that was created in the beginning was used to split the data sets back out to train and test sets. Unnecessary columns for imputation, correlation analysis, and prediction modeling were removed so as to avoid their effect on future results and then knn imputation was applied to the training set, which is the only data that includes our outcome of interest, sale price. This resulted in 1458 of the original 1460 observations being recovered and filled for 79 home features. Lastly, there was no duplicated data that needed to be addressed. All possible homes were elected to be kept and imputed in the dataset due to the number of observations being somewhat small and the confidence that their values could be imputed based on other factors that would ultimately help build a more robust overall model.

Plot 1¶
Here, we highlight some of the features that are specifically of interest to us in this work.


OverallQual rates the overall quality of the house. Building quality has a significant impact on house price; an improvement in quality from low to medium quality and from medium to high quality leads to home price increases by about 25% [5]. Our dataset ranks the quality of houses based on 10 categories, ranging from "Very Poor" to "Very Excellent."


GrLivArea is the above grade (ground) living area square feet. Size is crucial when assessing a home's market value because larger home tend to be of higher value. Homes that have larger living area compared to the typical sized homes in the neighborhood could be in greater demand and sold faster.


ExterQual evaluates the quality of the material on the exterior of the home. The exterior of a housecan attractmore buyers and increase the sale price. This feature has five categories from "poor" to "excellent."


KitchenQual is kitchen quality, another important feature to the sale price of a home. More than half of all homebuyers claim that the kitchen's qualitywas a major factor in their decision to purchase a particular home [6]. Kitchen quality is categorized into five categories from "poor" to "excellent."


GarageCars indicates the size of garage in car capacity. The presence of a garage is expected to increase the value of ahome.


GarageArea is the size of the garage in square feet. A larger garage should raise the selling value of a house and attract more buyers.


TotalBsmtSF is the total square feet of the basement area. A basement can remarkably increase the amount of usable living space in the home, and finishing this area can substantially increase the property's value.


The correlation plot above is reflective of the most correlated variables with sale price in the final imputed training set. It just so happens that all the most correlated variables are positively correlated with the outcome of interest. The plot is organized from most to least respectively correlated variables, but all variables show the same general pattern of increase as sale prices go up.

Plot 2¶
This plot shows us the relationship between sale price, above ground living area square footage, and kitchen quality. From the underlying scatterplot, it is evident that as the square footage of living space increases, so does the sale price, which isn't necessarily a surprising relationship. However, it seems that the majority of houses in the dataset fall between 1000 and 2000 square feet of living space, and some observations serve as proof that large square footage does not necessarily mean higher sale price, as the general trend would suggest. Breaking this relationship down further into how each house was ranked on kitchen quality, we can see how the condition of the home's interior determines more about the sale price than how much room (square feet) the house has available for use. The red line and points show houses whose kitchen quality was ranked (2) "Fair." You'll notice that there is a house with close to 3500 square feet of living space, but the low rated kitchen brings the sale price down. The trend goes on that way, with blue representing (3) "Typical/Average" rated kitchens, yellow indicating (4) "Good", and purple being those whose kitchen's were ranked as (5) "Excellent." It is notable to mention that higher quality kitchens naturally added to the home's value, but also that the purple homes are not necessarily that much bigger than the other homes in the dataset, indicating that quality may have more say over quanitity in this case on final sale price.

3 Interesting Questions¶
    

  1. Quality or quantity - which is more determinant of sale price? 
    2.

The breakdown and evaluation of Plot 2 paints a clearer picture of the way that quality seems to be of greater worth than quantity. In simpler terms,  a big house is not necessarily a nice house in Ames, Iowa, and a smaller home with higher quality features tends to go for more than a more sizable home of average grade.

    2. 



Plots 3 and 4 elucidate that interior and exterior quality explain a good amount of the variation in sale price (the definition of the coefficient of determination, which is correlation squared), and tend to be related to one another according to Plot 1. As interior quality goes up, exterior quality is expected to follow suit, as does sale price. This question was constituted to address whether there were any discrepancies among the homes in the dataset - if a home looks nice on the outside, is it safe for a potential home buyer to assume the inside will be just as nice? Plot 4 proves that there dont seem to be any rotten apples in the batch. As highlighted in its review, if a home was found to have above-average interior quality, its exterior quality was always average or better. The vice versa relationship from exterior to interior rankings can be observed in Plot 4 as well with a little more focus. On the flip side, below-average rated interior corresponded to average or equal rated exterior ratings among the homes in the set - and, again, the vice versa relationship can be observed. Plot 4 also demonstrates that homes whose exterior quality is better than their interior quality tend to have a slight edge in terms of the profitability gained when looking at the data through a qualitative lens - so, sale prices may be ever so slightly biased toward exterior quality, if at all. Still, the rankings do not waiver much within observations. This indicates that there is consistency within the homes of the dataset, which is encouraging from a simplicity standpoint in the housing market - what you see may actually be what you get - a nice thing to know going into the model building process.

Exceptional Work¶
UMAP Explanation¶
UMAP is a technique to reduce a high dimensional (high-d) dataset to low dimensional (low-d) and plot into a low-d graph to visualize the clusters and relationship between each point. In short, UMAP puts high-d points into a low-d graph, then adjusts the position of each point on the low-d graph until it has the same relationship in high-d.


UMAP takes two parameters, the number of nearest neighbors and minimum distance. It uses the number of nearest neighbors to plug in log2( # of nearest neighbor ), which determines the shape of the similarity score's curve. Similarity score is used to identify points that have a relationship with each other by its relative distance to each point, so when plotting a low-d graph, the clustering will still be the same in high-d. Then, use the minimum distance parameter in the low-d graph to space each point.


Then, UMAP uses Spectral Embedding to place each high-d point into a low-d graph, and adjust the distance between each point based on the low-d similarity scores derived from a t-distribution curve. If two points are close in high-d then UMAP wants to maximize the low-d similarity score, and vice versa for points that are far away.
